==English==
{{PIE root|en|gʰreyb}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|gripen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|grīpan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*grīpaną}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʰreyb-||to grab, grasp}}. Cognate with {{cog|fy|gripe}}, {{cog|nds|griepen}}, {{cog|nl|grijpen}}, {{cog|de|greifen}}, {{cog|da|gribe}}, {{cog|sv|gripa}}. See also {{m|en|grip}}, {{m|en|grope}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ɡɹʌɪp/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-gripe.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|aɪp|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|grip}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|intransitive}} To make a [[grab]] (''to'', ''towards'', ''at'' or ''upon'' something).
# {{lb|en|archaic|transitive}} To [[seize]], [[grasp]].
#* Robynson (More's Utopia)
#*: Wouldst thou '''gripe''' both gain and pleasure?
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[complain]]; to [[whine]].
#* {{quote-journal
|date=April 29, 2012
|author=Nathan Rabin
|title=TV: Review: THE SIMPSONS (CLASSIC): “Treehouse of Horror III” (season 4, episode 5; originally aired 10/29/1992)
|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/treehouse-of-horror-iii,72723/
|page=
|passage=In “Treehouse Of Horror” episodes, the rules aren’t just different—they don’t even exist. If writers want Homer to kill Flanders or for a segment to end with a marriage between a woman and a giant ape, they can do so without worrying about continuity or consistency or fans '''griping''' that the gang is behaving out of character.}}
# To suffer griping pains.
#: {{rfquotek|John Locke}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} To tend to come up into the wind, as a ship which, when sailing [[close-hauled]], requires constant labour at the helm.
#: {{rfquotek|R. H. Dana, Jr}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To [[pinch]]; to [[distress]]. Specifically, to cause pinching and spasmodic pain to the bowels of, as by the effects of certain purgative or indigestible substances.
#* Shakespeare
#*: How inly sorrow '''gripes''' his soul.

